2. Process Management Commands
Description: Implementation of commands used to monitor and control system processes.
Commands: ps (report process status), top (dynamic real-time view), kill (terminate a process), nice (change priority), and jobs.
In Linux, process management involves monitoring, controlling, and terminating the various tasks (processes) running on your system. Each process is assigned a unique **Process ID (PID)** used for identification.

- **Monitoring processes:** View active processes and resource consumption (CPU, memory).
- **Terminating & Controlling:** Stop or kill processes.
- **Managing Priority (Niceness):** Values range from -20 (Highest Priority) to 19 (Lowest Priority).
- **Job Control:** Manage tasks within the current terminal session.

## Commands Reference

| Sr. No | Command | Description |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1 | `applicationname &` | Runs any application in the background. |
| 2 | `pidof processname` | Returns process id of a running program. |
| 3 | `fg job_no` | Brings background job to foreground. |
| 4 | `top` | Shows live system processes and resource usage. |
| 5 | `kill pid` | Terminates a running process using PID. |
| 6 | `nice -n [val] [name]` | Starts a process with a specific priority. |
| 7 | `ps` | Shows processes in current terminal session. |
| 8 | `pstree` | Displays parent-child hierarchy of processes. |
| 9 | `ps aux` | Displays all processes with user/CPU/Mem details. |
| 10 | `ps -axjk` | Displays processes in hierarchical tree format. |
| 11 | `renice -n [val] [pid]` | Modifies priority of a running process. |
| 12 | `jobs` | Shows active background and stopped jobs. |
| 13 | `bg` | Resumes a suspended job in the background. |
| 14 | `killall [name]` | Kills all processes with a given name. |
| 15 | `pkill [name]` | Terminates process using name matching. |
